#Text=Revenge killings follow shooting of Karachi politician
#Text=Saturday , August 7 , 2010

#Text=Businesses remained closed for a second day on Wednesday in the Pakistani financial capital of Karachi , to mourn Raza Haider , a leading politician of the Muttahida Quami Movement ( MQM ) , assassinated on Monday .
#Text=Nineteen people were killed on Tuesday in revenge killings , bringing the death toll to 49 over two days .
#Text=Twenty-five shops and a number of vehicles including trucks and buses were burned in a series of arson attacks across the city .
#Text=Haider was gunned down while attending a funeral near the centre of the city .

#Text=An officer at the Nazimabad police station said " [ t]he number of attackers and the mode of their transport are not clear , but initial investigations suggest that there were more than two people who came on a motorcycle and they were probably backed by armed men in a car .

#Text=The Associated Press ( AP ) said that the MQM 's accusation  appeared to reflect the complex and vicious political and ethnic fault lines that crisscross Karachi . "

column1: #Text=The AP also said that Sharfuddin Memon , the head of the Citizen 's Police Liason Committee had speculated that Haider 's killing may be related to a government operation against " land mafias " , who illegally occupy commercially valuable land .
#Text=According to the AP 's report it is alleged that some of these mafias have the backing of political parties .
#Text=According to human rights organizations there have been more than 300 political killings in Karachi this year .
#Text=By Tuesday evening the Jinnah Post Graduate Medical Centre had received 17 dead bodies and 55 injured .
#Text=The head of the hospital , Dr Seemi Jamali , said that they had transfused 200 blood units to victims of targeted violence and that 31 gunshot victims had been operated upon that day .
#Text=This week 's wave of violence and attacks began with the assassination of Raza Haider , but due to the nature of Karachi politics the exact motive behind Haider 's murder is unclear .

#Text=The Associated Press commented that the city has long been plagued by political violence between supporters of rival parties " that draw votes from different ethnic groups in the city of 16 million people . "

column1: #Text=The publication said this muddied the reasons for the bloodshed .
#Text=Rehman Malik , Pakistan 's Interior Minister was quoted by media as saying Islamist militants were likely suspects .
#Text=He said that Haider had been on the extremist hit list .

#Text=The BBC reported that they had been told by security officials in Karachi that there is evidence to suggest the assassination was carried out by the Lashkar-e-Jhangvi , Pakistan 's deadliest militant group .
#Text=The BBC News website also reported that senior MQM leader Babar Ghauri had said : " Every MQM activist will now be looking to pay back the people involved in this heinous act " .
#Text=Raza Haider was laid to rest on Tuesday at the Martyr 's Graveyard in Azizabad , northern Karachi .
#Text=Hundreds of MQM members and supporters attended to pay their final respects to Haider and to his guard Khalid Khan , also killed in the shooting .
#Text=The funeral took place under tight security , and with activists raising slogans against the violence that has gripped the city .
